specialcase.p:
Consider the linear system

        \syseq{2x + y + 12z = 1; x + 2y + 9z = -1\rlap.}

      We solve it using row reduction:


          \amat{2 1 12 1; 1 2 9 -1}
          \quad\xrightarrow{R_1 \longleftrightarrow R_2}\quad
          &\amat{\color{red}1 2 9 -1; 2 1 12 1}
          &&\color{blue}\text{(Optional)}


          {}\quad\xrightarrow{R_2=R_2-2R_1}\quad
          &\amat{1 2 9 -1; \color{red}0 -3 -6 3}
          &&\color{blue}\text{(Step 1c)}


          {}\quad\xrightarrow{R_2=R_2\div -3}\quad
          &\amat{1 2 9 -1; 0 \color{red}1 2 -1}
          &&\color{blue}\text{(Step 2b)}


          {}\quad\xrightarrow{R_1=R_1-2R_2}\quad
          &\amat{1 \color{red}0 5 1; 0 1 2 -1}
          &&\color{blue}\text{(Step 2c)}


      This row reduced matrix corresponds to the linear system

        \syseq{x + 5z = 1; y + 2z = -1\rlap.}

      In what sense is the system solved?  We rewrite as

        \syseq{x = 1 - 5z; y = -1 - 2z\rlap.}

      For any value of z, there is exactly one value of x and y that make the equations true.  But we are free to choose any value of z.

We have found all solutions: it is the set of all values x,y,z, where

        \syseq{x = 1 - 5z; y = -1 - 2z; z = \. \+ z} \qquad \text{$z$ any real number.}

	This is called the parametric form for the solution to the linear system.  The variable z is called a free variable.

subsection.p:
In the above , the variable \color{red}z was free because the reduced row echelon form matrix was
    \def\r{\color{red}}
      \amat{1 0 \r5 1; 0 1 \r2 -1}.

    In the matrix
    \amat{
    1  \color{seq-red}\star,  0  \color{seq-blue}\star,  \star ;
    0  \color{seq-red}0   1  \color{seq-blue}\star,  \star
    },

    the free variables are \color{seq-red}x_2 and \color{seq-blue}x_4.  (The augmented column is not free because it does not correspond to a variable.)

note.p:
The solution set of the system of linear equations

        \syseq{2x + y + 12z = 1; x + 2y + 9z = -1}

      is a line in \R^3, as we saw in this .  These equations are called the implicit equations for the line: the line is defined implicitly as the simultaneous solutions to those two equations.

The parametric form

        \syseq{x = 1 - 5z; y = -1 - 2z\rlap.}

      can be written as follows:

        (x,\,y,\,z) = (1-5z,\,-1-2z,\,z) \qquad \text{$z$ any real number.}

      This is called a parameterized equation for the same line.  It is an expression that produces all points of the line in terms of one parameter, z.

example.p:
Suppose that the reduced row echelon form of the matrix for a linear system in four variables x_1,x_2,x_3,x_4 is
\amat{
1 \color{seq-red}0 0 \color{seq-blue}3 2 ;
0 \color{seq-red}0 1 \color{seq-blue}4 -1
}.
The free variables are \color{seq-red}x_2 and \color{seq-blue}x_4: they are the ones whose columns are not pivot columns.

This translates into the system of equations

        \syseq{x_1 \+ \. \+ \. + 3x_4 = 2;
        \.  \+ \. \+ x_3 + 4x_4 = -1}
        \quad\xrightarrow{\text{parametric form}}\quad
        \syseq{x_1 = 2 - 3x_4; x_3 = -1 - 4x_4\rlap.}

      What happened to x_2?  It is a free variable, but no other variable depends on it.  The general solution to the system is
      (x_1,\,x_2,\,x_3,\,x_4) = (2-3x_4,\,x_2,\,-1-4x_4,\,x_4),
      for any values of x_2 and x_4.  For instance, (2,0,-1,0) is a solution (with x_2=x_4=0), and (5,1,3,-1) is a solution (with x_2=1, x_4=-1).
